Description¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms, and provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Data Description¶

The data provided is of various customers of a bank and their financial attributes like credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customers have contacted the bank for any queries (including visiting the bank, online and through a call center).

Data Dictionary¶

Sl_No: Primary key of the records
Customer Key: Customer identification number
Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards
Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer
Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

K-means clustering¶

In [27]:
# Plotting the Elbow curve to analyze the number of clusters

clusters = range(1, 11)
meanDistortions = []

for cls in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=cls)
    model.fit(scaled_cls_data)
    prediction = model.predict(scaled_cls_data)
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(scaled_cls_data, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / scaled_cls_data.shape[0]
    )
    meanDistortions.append(distortion)
    print("Cluster Number: {0} , Distortion: {1} ".format(cls, distortion))

plt.figure(figsize=(16, 12))
plt.xlabel("K(Cluster)")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Displaying Elbow Curve and selecting the optimum k for cluster.")
plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "-o")

def plot_silhouette_visualizer(df, cluster):
    """
    Method to plot silhouette visualizer with given dataframe and cluster number
    """
    visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(KMeans(cluster, random_state=1))
    visualizer.fit(df)
    visualizer.show()

Business Recommendations Based on K-means clustering¶

  • Cluster 0 and Cluster 3: These customers maintain more number good number of credit cards but with lower limits. They also have highest number of bank visits that means they wanted to continue their relationship with bank.They are not frequent caller to bank to query or resolve issues.

    Bank can approach and organize training for online access of bank application to reduce their bank visits.This will lower the cost for bank per customer. Also understand their reason for visit and offer them to increase their credit limit after completion of training program, make them aware of features for different credit cards

  • Cluster 1: This cluster customers has lowest credit limit, lowest number of credit cards and lower number of bank visits. They are well visiting bank portal online more than cluster 0 and cluster 3 but they are also making most calls to bank. Considering all points, we can say customer may belongs to lower income group or they have just started new job or they are living far off places from any bank branch and moderately trained to use online features.

    Bank can offer family credit card for whole family tied to principal applicant. Offer online training for customer/whole family to show different credit card product to choose as per need or as per each family member need. Easy step to increase credit limit. To reduce number of calls bank can also train train them to use mobile app and virtual chat features

  • Cluster 2 : These customers can be considered premium customers. They are well informed, tech savvy and well aquatinted with all features of online application , rules and regulation. Therefore , they are making less call to bank. Cost to maintain such customers is less.

    They can be targeted for online campaign to promote new credit card with additional perks for being good customer, They can be offered easy step to increase existing credit limit or targeted first whenever bank is launching any new credit card product

# List of Distance Metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

# List of Linkage Methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]


def get_cluster_metrics(df, dist_metric_list, linkage_list):

    max_coeff = 0
    max_dm_lm = [0, 0]

    for dist in dist_metric_list:
        for link in linkage_list:
            Z = linkage(df, method=link, metric=dist)
            coeff, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(scaled_cls_data))
            print(
                "Metric: {0}, Linkage: {1}, Cophenet Coefficient: {2}".format(
                    dist.capitalize(), link.capitalize(), coeff
                )
            )
            if max_coeff < coeff:
                max_coeff = coeff
                max_dm_lm[0] = dist
                max_dm_lm[1] = link

    print(
        "\nMaximum cophenet Coefficient Obtained using Metric: {0}, Linkage: {1},\nCophenet Coefficient:{2}".format(
            max_dm_lm[0].capitalize(), max_dm_lm[1].capitalize(), max_coeff
        )
    )


get_cluster_metrics(scaled_cls_data, distance_metrics, linkage_methods)

# Get the customers for each cluster
def cluster_count(df):
    """
    Method to get the number of customers for each cluster for a given dataset
    """
    for cl in df["HC_Clusters"].unique():
        cust = df[df["HC_Clusters"] == cl]["Customer_Key"]
        print("Cluster {0} has {1} customers. These are".format(cl, cust.nunique()))
        print(cust.unique())
        print("-" * 100)
        print()

# Box plot given dataset.
def cluster_box_plotfig(df, row, col, type):
    """
    Boxplot given dataset in given row and column formation
    """
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(row, col, figsize=(16, 12))
    fig.suptitle(
        "Boxplot of {0} numerical variables for each cluster".format(type),
        fontsize=20,
    )
    counter = 1
    for ii in range(row):
        if counter <= len(num_cols) - 1:
            sns.boxplot(
                ax=axes[ii][0],
                y=df[num_cols[counter]],
                x=df["HC_Clusters"],
            )
        counter = counter + 1
        if counter <= len(num_cols) - 1:
            sns.boxplot(
                ax=axes[ii][1],
                y=df[num_cols[counter]],
                x=df["HC_Clusters"],
            )
        counter = counter + 1

    fig.tight_layout(pad=2.0)

Business Recommendations Based on Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • Cluster 0: This cluster customers has lowest credit limit, lowest number of credit cards and lower number of bank visits , they are visiting bank portal online more than cluster 1 and cluster 3 But making most calls to customer care.Possibly, these customers belongs to lower income group or they have just started new job or they are living far off places from any bank branch.

    Bank can offer family credit card for whole family tied to principal applicant. Offer online training for customer/whole family to show different credit card product to choose as per need or as per each family member need. Easy step to increase credit limit. To reduce number of calls bank can also train train them to use mobile app and virtual chat features

  • Cluster 1 and Cluster 3: These customers maintain more number good number of credit cards but with lower limits. They also have highest number of bank visits that means they wanted to continue their relationship with bank.In additon they are not that much tech savvy. They are making moderate number number of calls to bank.

    Bank can approach and organize training for online access of bank application to reduce their bank visits.This will lower the cost for bank per customer. Also understand their reason for visit and offer them to increase their credit limit after completion of training program, make them aware of features for different credit cards

  • Cluster 2 : These customers can be considered premium customers. They are well informed, tech savvy and well aquainted with bank rules and product features making less number of calls to bank. Therefore, cost to maintain such customers is less.

    They can be targeted for online campaign to promote new credit card with additional perks for being good customer, They can be offered easy step to increase existing credit limit or targeted first whenever bank is launching any new credit card product

Cluster Comparison and Additional Details¶

  • K-Means clustering took less time to execute than Hierarchical Clustering because it spend more time in generating dendrograms.

  • However, Hierarchical Clustering gave clear visualization through dendrograms to decide right number of clusters.

  • Silhouette score details are mentioned plot wise for each cluster. it addition to that , it was highest for cluster 3(score: 0.52), then it went down sharply until cluster 5(0.27) and then started flattening after it .

  • Observation in similar cluster of both algorithms

    K_means_segments: 190, 221, 199, 50 HC_Clusters : 196,223, 191, 50

    For most of the clusters observations are differing slightly for extremely large data set this will be negligible difference. For one of the cluster observation is exactly matching.

  • In both the case, K-Means clustering and Hierarchical Clustering appropriate number of clusters is 4. We can conclusively say that they are generating similar cluster. Therefore, insight and recommendation are almost same.

  • These insight and recommendation are based on limited data and limited number of feature. It may differ if we have too many features and records.
